Nevertheless, respiratory disorders and failure are the main threat to the patient and the main cause of death.
Respiratory support is therefore crucial for relieving symptoms and saving lives, including regular oxygen absorption, high flow oxygen absorption, non-generative gas and mechanical ventilation, depending on the severity of the disease.
Patients with severe symptoms of the respiratory system must receive endometrial oxygen (ECMO) support, which is an improved cardiovascular side technology for the treatment of life-threatening heart or respiratory failure.
Furthermore, the maintenance of the electrolyte balance, prevention and treatment of post-infectious and urotoxic shocks and the protection of important organ functions are also essential for SARS-CoV-2 patients.
It is known that an excessive immune system reaction in SARS and MERS patients can lead to a cell-factor storm.
Cell-factor storm is a form of a whole body inflammatory reaction, characterized by the release of a number of cell factors, including TNFα, IL-1β, IL-2, IL-6, IFNα, IFNβ, IFNγ and MCP-1.
These cell factors can trigger the immune cells to release a large amount of free genes, which is the main cause of ARDS and multiorgan failure.
Immunodepression is crucial in the treatment of cell-factor storms, especially in severe patients.
Corticosteroids and Toughened Laminated Safety Glass – an anti-IL6 single-clone antibodies – have already been used to treat cell factor storms.
Other immunosuppressant therapies aimed at cell-factor storm include: regulating cell-oriented immunosuppressant response; blocking IFN-γ, IL-1 and TNF; inhibiting JAK; Bonnar monotonous resistance; cell-factor signal transmission inhibitors 4; and HDAC inhibitors.
Steroids as an immune inhibitor are widely used in the treatment of SARS to reduce the severity of inflammatory damage.
However, large doses of steroid are not beneficial for severe lungs in SARS and COVID-19 patients.
On the contrary, they can cause severe side effects, especially anemia, and thus seriously affect prognosis.
Nevertheless, it is still recommended that COVID-19 patients with severe disease take careful short-term therapy with medium-low doses of corticosteroid.
At the time of writing this article, the existence of effective antiviral therapy has not yet been confirmed.
