It is necessary to update COVID-19 diagnostic standards for “such cases” and “diagnosed cases”
On February 6, 2020, our team published the 2019 New Coronavirus (2019-nCoV) Infection Diagnostic and Treatment Fast Recommendation Guide, which provides experience and expertise for global epidemic response.
However, 2019 coronavirus disease (COVID-19) is a new type of disease, based on the results of the research and clinical practice experience, our awareness of the disease is gradually improving; therefore, diagnosis and treatment strategies are also constantly updated.
In this letter, we responded to one of the opinions on the above guidelines and provided the latest diagnosis standards for “such cases” and “diagnostic cases” in accordance with the latest COVID-19 Clinical Program published by the National Health Committee of the People’s Republic of China (Seventh Edition).
In December 2019, the 2019 new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) exploded, currently the disease has been officially named 2019 coronavirus disease (COVID-19), the virus had been named severe acute respiratory syndrome type 2 coronavirus (SARS-CoV-2).
On 11 March 2020, the World Health Organization (WHO) classified COVID-19 as a global major epidemic.
To fight SARS-CoV-2 infection, our team has developed a quick guidance and published the guidance online in the Journal of Military Medical Research on February 6, 2020.
Since its release, it has attracted extensive attention.
But please note that COVID-19 is a new type of disease, based on the research results and clinical practice experience, our awareness of the disease is gradually improving; therefore, diagnosis and treatment strategies are also constantly updated.
For example, the National Health Committee of the People's Republic of China (http://www.nhc.gov.cn/) published a total of seven editions of the COVID-19 Clinical Program between 16 January 2020 and 3 March 2020, some of which have been substantially changed.
Now, our guidelines have received opinions from people like Zhou, who have proposed a simple rating scheme based on their clinical experience.
Their work provides new evidence for our guidelines and also provides valuable references to this global epidemic.
We recognize this important work they do and thank you.
However, their proposals need to be updated on the basis of the latest COVID-19 Clinical Program (Test Seventh Edition) and recent research.
According to the 7th edition (3 March 2020), the diagnosis of suspicious cases requires a combination of an epidemic history characteristic with two clinical manifestations for a comprehensive analysis, which requires three clinical manifestations if there is no clear epidemic history:
Epidemiological history: (1) a history of travel or residence in communities that have COVID-19 cases within 14 days before the occurrence of the symptoms; (2) a history of contact with SARS-CoV-2 infections (Nucleic Acid Detection is Positive); (3) a history of contact with fever or respiratory symptoms in communities that have COVID-19 during 14 days before the occurrence of the symptoms; and (4) a history of contact with aggregate diagnosis cases (in the 2 weeks before the occurrence of the symptoms, in a small scale of contact with ≥ 2 cases of fever and/or respiratory symptoms, such as at home, office, school)
Clinical manifestations: (1) fever and/or respiratory symptoms; (2) imagistic characteristics of COVID-19 infection; (3) the total number of early white cells of the disease is normal or decreased, and the number of lymphatic cells is reduced.
The diagnosis of cases should be based on suspicious cases and with any of the following pathogenic or serumic evidence: (1) the real-time PCR test for SARS-CoV-2 is positive; (2) the viral genome sequence shows the highest homogeneity with the known new coronavirus; (3) the specific IgM and IgG antibodies for SARS-CoV-2 in the serum test are positive; or the specific IgG antibodies for SARS-CoV-2 are negative to positive, or the drop rate increases ≥ 4 times during the recovery period, higher than the acute period.
We can see that the second edition (18 January 2020) and the third edition (22 January 2020) adds PCR nucleic acid testing in real-time in the respiratory tract or blood samples.
The fourth edition (27 January 2020) and the fifth edition (8 February 2020) added blood sample pathogenic testing; the seventh edition added blood serum evidence.
These amendments are based on the researchers' continued work of the best Nucleic Acid Test Box for rapid diagnosis, as well as breathing patterns, including blood clotting, which increased the availability of different patterns and provided evidence of the inclusion of positive results of specific antibodies in the diagnosis standard.
Moreover, more and more evidence reminds us of not typical symptoms and non-symptomatic patients.
Therefore, the process map of people like Zhou should be updated, as they will classify people without clinical symptoms as "low-risk".
Moreover, the rating system needs to be verified in further clinical practice and research.
Finally, we want more direct evidence to appear and call on the readers to make their opinions.
For the diagnosis of "such cases" and "diagnostic cases", we recommend reference and follow the latest guidelines for the country where the case is located.
Our team will also update our guidelines in time to provide help.
