COVID-19 Workplace Control
COVID-19 workplace prevention means the adoption of risk-controlled occupational safety and health measures to prevent coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19).
The proper risk control at work depends on the specific workplace and work tasks and should be determined on the basis of the risk assessment of the source of exposure, the severity of community diseases and the risk factors that may be exposed to COVID-19.
According to the requirements of the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), low-risk exposure work is the minimum contact with the work of the public and other colleagues, so it is recommended to take basic infectious prevention measures, including working handwashing, encouraging workers to post-healing home isolation, adhere to breathing rituals, and daily cleaning and disinfection of the work environment.
Medium exposure risk work includes the need for frequent or close contact with the work of unknown or suspicious COVID-19 patients who may be infected due to continued community spread or international travel.
Includes access to general public staff, such as schools, a high-density work environment and some large-scale retail environments.
In addition to basic infection prevention measures, the group should also use efficient air filters and spray protection devices to ventilate, wear personal protection equipment when exposed to COVID-19 patients and take other hazardous prevention measures.
OSHA believes that the exposure to known or suspicious COVID-19 patients has a high risk of exposure, and that the exposure risks are very high if the staff performs a gas-soluble operation on known or suspicious COVID-19 patients, or collect or process samples from them.
Risk control measures applicable to such persons include engineering controls, such as pressure ventilation rooms and personal protection equipment suitable for their work tasks.
The COVID-19 explosion may have a serious impact on the workplace.
The staff may be absent due to illness, need to take care of others or fear of exposure.
Business patterns may also change, including a change in the demand for goods, or a change in the way to get these goods (such as shopping in non-top times, or using delivery or off-road shipping services).
Finally, the logistics of products from COVID-19 epidemic areas may be interrupted. infection prevention and response programs can be used to guide protection actions.
These programs address risks related to various workplaces and work tasks, including exposure sources, risk factors from the family and community environment, and risk factors for individual workers, such as elderly or groups with chronic diseases.
These plans also summarize the preventive measures needed to address these risks, as well as the emergency plans for cases that may arise as a result of the epidemic.
Infectious Disease Prevention and Response Programs may require state or local recommendations.
The objectives to address the epidemic include reducing the spread between employees, protecting people with a high risk of malhealth complications,ining business operations, and maximizing the negative effects on other entities in the supply chain.
In addition, the response measures will also be affected by the severity of the disease in the community where the enterprise is located.
Risk prevention level is a prevention framework that is widely used in occupational safety and health, and is used to group risks prevention measures according to their effectiveness.
If the damage of COVID-19 cannot be completely eliminated, the most effective control measures are engineering controls, followed by administrative controls, and finally personal protection equipment.
Engineering control means isolating employees from work-related risks rather than relying on employees’ behavior to control, which is also the lowest cost solution to implement.
Administrative control means changing work policies or procedures that require employees or employers to take action on their own.
Personal protection equipment (PPE) has a lower control effect than engineering control and administrative control, but it helps prevent some exposure.
All types of PPEs must be selected according to the risk levels faced by the staff, equipped according to the applicability (such as a respirator) and must always be properly worn, regularly checked andined, replaced if necessary and properly removed, cleaned, stored or processed in order to avoid pollution.
According to the regulations of the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), low exposure risk work is the lowest contact with the public and other colleagues in the profession.
It is recommended that all workplaces take basic infectious prevention measures, including handwashing, advising the sick employees to adhere to the breathing methods when they are isolated from the home, coughing or spotting, providing paper towels and rubbish, preparing for remote office, falling out of work if necessary, encouraging employees to use the tools and equipment of others, and keeping the workplaces daily clean and disinfected.
The timely identification and isolation of potential infectious individuals is the key to protecting workplace staff, customers, visitors and others.
The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) recommends that employees with acute respiratory symptoms be isolated at least 24 hours until there are no fever, fever signs and any other symptoms, the vacation policy should be flexibly implemented, allowing employees to take care of the patient’s families and should clearly inform the employees of the policy.
According to OSHA, medium exposure risk work includes the need for frequent or close contact with unknown or suspicious COVID-19 patients within a range of 6 feet (1.8 m), but may cause individuals to become SARS-CoV-2 infected because of the continued spread of the community near the workplace or because they may have recently arrived in the COVID-19 epidemic area.
This type of staff includes working in schools, a high-population working environment and some large-scale retail environment that will be in contact with the general public staff. Engineering control measures aimed at this group and high-risk groups include the installation of efficient air filters, improved ventilation effects, transparent plastic spread protection devices, etc. Installing physical barriers and the installation of free-of-car windows to provide customer service. Administrative controls for this group and high-risk groups include encouraging the isolation of the sick staff home, replacing face-to-face meetings with virtual communications, establishing an unnecessary journey to the COVID-19 explosion site, developing an emergency communications plan, including answering the staff's questions for the forum, providing staff with the latest training and training on the COVID-19 risk factors and behavior protection, using the need for the protection and protection of the protection and protection of the protection of the work
This type of staff is best required to have a breathing machine.
If someone is sick on the plane, appropriate protective measures should be taken to protect the staff and other passengers, including arranging the patient to a distance of 6 feet from the other passengers, appointing a crew staff to serve the patient, providing the patient with a mask, or asking the patient to cover the mouth with a paper towel when it is coughed or sprayed.
The crew staff should wear one-time medical gloves when treating sick passengers, touching body fluids or potential pollution surface.The crew staff should also wear additional personal protection equipment if sick passengers experience symptoms such as fever, persistent coughing or breathing difficulties.
The gloves and other one-time items should be treated in a bio-dangerous bag and then respond to the polluted surface for cleaning and disinfection. for commercial transport, including tourboats and other passenger vessels, hazard control measures also include delaying travel when ill. If there is a heat or other symptoms on the vessel, it should be self-isolated and immediately inform the medical room on the vessel.
For schools and children’s care sites, the disease prevention control center recommends that the relevant schools and children’s care sites be closed in the short term, regardless of the spread of the community, if the infected person has appeared in the school, to be completely cleaned or disinfected.
For medium-sized communities, social distances can be implemented, such as the cancellation of field visits, meetings and sports classes, singing classes or self-help restaurants, the increase of the distance between office tables, mistake of arrival and departure, the limitation of unnecessary visitors, and the separate health offices for children with flu symptoms.
If the community spreads seriously, it may be considered to extend the interruption time in addition to implementing social distance strategies.For law enforcement personnel performing regular daily activities, the Prevention Control Center believes that they face a lower direct health risk.
It is recommended that patients diagnosed with COVID-19 or suspicious persons of law enforcement should act at the same level of protection as emergency medical technicians, including equipped with appropriate personal protection equipment.
If a close contact occurs in the process of arrest, the staff must first clean and disinfect their work belt and equipment, then can be reused after using domestic cleansing spray or clay cleansing, and must comply with the standard personal protection equipment cover and treatment procedures, as well as clothing cover and cleansing procedures.
OSHA believes that some healthcare and hospital staff are at high or very high exposure risks.
High exposure risk staff include medical care, support, laboratory and medical transport staff for known or suspected COVID-19 infected persons.
The risk of exposure becomes extremely high if the staff performs bubble-generation procedures on known or suspicious COVID-19 patients, or collect or treat samples of infected or suspicious infected people.
The bubble-generation processes include injection pipe, cough provokation processes, tuberculosis examinations, some dental procedures and examinations, or body oral samples collection.
High exposure risk staff include staff involved in the handling of the dead's bodies, who were diagnosed or suspicious cases of COVID-19; exposure risks are higher if the body's anatomy is carried out. Additional engineering measures to be taken for this risk group include the isolation rooms prepared for the COVID-19 diagnosed or suspicious cases, including during the execution of the bubble-generation process.
Some healthcare facilities and mortgage rooms can also be equipped with a special pressure ventilation system.
Biosafety Level 3 preventive measures should be taken during the processing of samples.
The World Health Organization (WTO) recommends different waiting zones for patients depending on whether the patient is suspicious of COVID-19.In addition to other personal protection equipment, the Office of Occupational Safety and Health also recommends that people who work within a 6-foot range of patients with known or suspected SARS-CoV-2 infection, as well as those who perform a bubble-generation process, wear a respiratory device.
The U.S. requires that a comprehensive breath protection program, such as health tests, training, and medical examinations, should use a N95 filter mask or a better mask approved by NIOSH.
Other types of respiratory devices can provide better protection and improve the comfort of the staff.WHO does not recommend using protective clothes because COVID-19 is a respiratory disease that does not spread through body fluids.
The WHO recommends that entrance checkers only wear medical surgical masks.
For staff who need to collect respiratory samples from COVID-19 patients and provide care or transfer services to patients without the need to carry out bubble-generating procedures, the WHO recommends that they use medical surgical masks, care glasses or masks, clothes and gloves.
If you want to perform the bubble generation procedure, the medical surgical mask must be replaced with the N95 or FFP2 mask.
Given the lack of global supply of personal protection equipment, the WHO recommends physical barriers, such as remote care, transparent windows, allowing only direct careers to enter the rooms of COVID-19 patients, using personal protection equipment only when specific tasks are truly necessary, continuing to use the same respirator when treating multiple patients with the same diagnosis results, monitoring and coordinating the supply chain of personal protection equipment, and measures such as not encouraging non-symptomatic people to use masks to reduce the need for personal protection equipment.
Publisher: Chairman of the Wikimedia Foundation, Katherine Maher
Recipient: All employees of the Wikimedia Foundation
Subject: [Covid-19] Close up and prepare for the future
Delivery Date/Time: March 14, 2020 00:24 (World Time Coordination)
License: CC0: No rights reserved
We have experienced some difficult situations since this month.
In the face of the COVID-19 epidemic, we clearly feel the fate of the whole humanity, and at the same time recognize our responsibility to each other.
We face unprecedented challenges, but we know that the best way to tackle this challenge requires people around the world to feel compassionate, co-operate and promote community building, which is the core idea of Wikimedia.
The communication of friendship and care between all our colleagues through e-mails, telephones and chats fully proves how different our colleagues are and how we are lucky to work with you.
I am very grateful and proud to be a colleague with you.
Last week, some expressed appreciation for our work.
They make me realize how meaningful it is to use Wikipedia around the world at this moment, and make me realize that this key resource keeps the symbolic power that it brings to people around the world.
Whether your job is responsible for the operation of the website, payments or community security, the proper operation of Wikimedia is unchanged with your hard work.
Today’s world needs more information from Wikipedia than ever.
At this stage, the contents of our work and even the way we work will have a significant impact on the world.
Given the importance of this mission and the importance of our colleagues, we will make some important changes to our way of cooperation starting next week.
Modification of working method and timetable
As Robyn previously mentioned, the executive team met yesterday night to discuss the way and timetables the company works in the next few days to months.
At the meeting, we considered the appropriate response we consider to the current challenges faced by the company, as well as the best practices to ensure that the companyins sustainable development during the epidemic.
The executive team unanimously agreed to reduce the pressure on the company’s employees, allowing everyone to support the company’s mission for a long time.
We support you to adequately reduce work pressure.
For all employees, contractors and contractual workers:
Our daily working hours will be adjusted to 4 hours a day (or 20 hours a week) and subsequent changes will be notified separately.
This adjustment is not a vacation notice.If you can work longer a day, we will arrange tasks for you according to the length of your work time.
However, as the current world situation is unpredictable, we will prioritize taking care of your personal needs, such as taking care of your family, shopping out or medical consultations.
We will not track your working hours.
If you are sick, leave your job.
This is unclear, but we still want to remind you, please be calm.
You don’t need to apply for a sick leave or paid leave, but you need to inform the manager and help your team modify the work schedule and timetables to ensure that critical work areas are not affected.
(If you are diagnosed with COVID-19 positive, please tell the staff and cultural operations department of Bryan, which will provide you with support and ensure your situation gets the appropriate attention of the management.)
We will pay full wages for timely wages employees.
We have expressed and again committed to complying with the commitments made to contractors and time workers.
The salary we pay to all will continue to be calculated according to the remuneration they obtained by completing normal working hours in normal conditions.
Even if you are sick or unable to work is no exception.
If you are willing to work, we will provide you with support.
Many people choose to communicate with the outside world through work, releasing their own pressure.
Our work can bring incredible rewards, especially in this time.
But taking care of yourself remains the first.
We ask you to keep in communication with the manager so that we can learn about your latest situation and make the corresponding adjustments.
Priority of important work.
We need to maintain the normal functioning of some important work.
Web site reliability engineering teams, human resources operating teams, trust and security teams and funding teams (and other teams) work are crucial, which may require additional support.
We will begin to evaluate the current project targets with all the departments and move work focus on supporting some of the matters that are crucial to our mission.
We all have a lot of work to do, but we all need to focus on the most important projects.
The temporarily slowing steps will not affect future development.
We don’t intend to “upgrade overtime” after the epidemic.
We will not ask you for overtime tracking periods, because now it seems unrealistic.
We accept that the current environment has changed and we will set new goals and timetables as appropriate.
What will change in the APP (Annual Plan)?
In order to adapt to the new realities and daily working hours requirements, we plan to adjust the delivery schedule for the 2020-2021 year plan.
We want to propose an extension of the 2019-2020 program in exchange for more time spent on budgeting, allowing employees to prioritize critical jobs and take care of themselves and their families, and also to adjust work arrangements for those who need or wish to reduce the amount of work in the coming weeks.
The extension of the timetable can significantly reduce the current planned work volume throughout the organization and reduce the work pressure.
We will submit the above proposals to the Board next week.If the proposal is approved, we will update the following work arrangements to the representatives and teams as soon as possible.
Thank you for the leadership of the APP team in this process.
Office condition, exposure and cleaning
Last week, we learned that a colleague at a San Francisco office might have been exposed to the COVID-19 virus.
However, for careful consideration, we hired some antivirus cleansers to make a complete disinfection of the San Francisco office.
They use hospital-class disinfection solutions to disinfect various surfaces, as well as between the halls and elevators that go to our floor.
The office building is fulfilling its attention obligation agreement, using the corresponding products to ensure the safety of the tenant.
We believe that when you decide to return to work, the office is fully prepared to welcome you.
Our Washington D.C. office adopts the WeWork office, and WeWork shares the COVID-19 agreement with us and all Washington D.C. staff.
As of last week, the Washington D.C. Office has changed to a full-fledged office in accordance with the guidelines we have shared with the San Francisco Office.
At the same time, as some New York offices’ colleagues already know, we’ve been discussing the issues related to rent offices in the Brooklyn District.
These discussions continue, but may be delayed.
Some of the colleagues first contacted the remote office.
Other colleagues in the long-term office want to give these colleagues some adjustment advice on the way they work:
Meeting time should be controlled within one to two hours.
If it takes a longer time, consider distributing the content of the meeting to several dates in the meeting.
Defining clearly the objectives of the meeting, drawing up the agenda of the meeting, and sending reading materials in advance.
Use video meetings as a default meeting mode while using tools such as Google Docs and Zoom to collaborate and communicate online.
In each meeting, organize a chairman to host a meeting, organize a person responsible for monitoring questions in the chat window and track the changes in the speaker list, and organize another person responsible (or using a multi-person collaboration method) to help make a meeting record.
If you need a comfortable headset, please send an email to contact the technical support department.
Use your health subsidy to buy snacks.
Join the #remoties channel on Slack to discuss distributed work with colleagues
The Human Resource Operating Team is studying Human Engineering Guidelines in the form of a network seminar to help the Foundation’s all colleagues improve their work efficiency during the distributed office.
Last week, we asked all community recipients to cancel public activities financed by Wikimedia, including editors, before the WHO announced the end of the epidemic.
These requests for cancellation of activities and other restrictions may cause these community recipients to fail to complete their original donation activities, and we have told them that we understand this and also promise that no one of them will be punished for delaying or changing these goals.
During the next week, we will continue to provide more guidance on Wikimedia and other regional community meetings and thematic community meetings.
The global community seems to be covered with the sadness of the epidemic, but it also reflects compassion for being able to clearly keep attention to their respective communities, Wikimedia and other aspects.
In the future, the CRT team will build a page on Meta-Wiki to provide a space for the community to monitor the influence and track the community’s communication with us.
Keep in touch, communicate with COVID-19 related issues
We are scheduled to hold a special staff meeting on Thursday 14:00 (World Coordination Time) 07:00 (Pacific Time) and we will send the relevant invitations to your calendar later.
At the meeting, we will share some of the latest situations, answer your questions and leave some time for discussions.
We are united and are committed to helping you.
At the same time, you can learn more about the information mentioned in this email and other important information related to COVID-19 on the Office Wiki.
The CRT team will update these pages in time and concentrate all the information in one place.
We are trying to maintain regular communication with employees living in countries/regions that are currently seriously affected by the epidemic.
If you have any questions regarding travel, activities, major work processes or insurance, or need help in other aspects, please contact and collaborate with the CRT team at any time.
We are committed to providing you with the support and contact you need.
If you have any confidential or sensitive questions, please send an email to the Global Human Resource Operations Director Bryan Judan.
Although we face these changes, we cannot give up our work and our obligations.
Instead, this epidemic makes us realize that we may now need to make adjustments to our work and obligations in a way that has not been before.
We believe that these measures are necessary to help us support each other to continue to work, to provide the necessary support for our actions, and to continue to bring the services they depend on to the world.
Make a plan and do not be afraid of challenges.
Now, please support each other and create space for important work in the next few weeks or even months.
We need everyone to contribute to this goal, so please take care of yourself and your family so that you can stay in the best condition when needed.
Finally, please keep in mind to wash your hands and not touch your face.
