Angiotensin-converting enzyme 2 (ACE2) is an enzyme attached to the cell outer surface (cell membrane) in the lungs, arteries, heart, kidneys and intestines.
ACE2 suppresses the activity of the associated angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) by reducing the content of vascular stress II and increasing the content of Ang(1-7) and is expected to be a drug target for the treatment of cardiovascular diseases.
The source version of this enzyme is usually called hACE2.
The vascular stress converter enzyme 2 is a zinc-containing metal enzyme located on the surface of the intramuscular cells and other cells.
The ACE2 protein contains a N-End Protein M2 structure area and a C-End Collectrin renal amino acid transmission protein structure area.
ACE2 is a single-type I membrane protein, its enzyme active structure area exposed to the cell surface of the lungs and other tissues.
Another enzyme known as sheddase (sheddase) disperses the outcellular structure of ACE2 from the transmembrane structure, releasing the produced soluble protein into the blood and eventually emitting it into the urine.
ACE2 is present in most organs: ACE2 is attached to the cell membrane, mainly the pneumonia type II cells of the lungs, the adrenal cells of the small intestines, the arteric and endocrine cells of the most organs, and the arteric smooth muscle cells.
The expression of ACE2 mRNA is also found in the cortex of the brain, the tissue body, the lower cortex and the mouth dry.
The main function of ACE2 is to balance the ACE.
ACE divides vascular tension I into vascular tension II that is active in vascular contraction.
ACE2 subsequently dissolves the end-mineral amino acid of Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe (Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-Phe) and hydrates it into a vascular tension (1-7), which is active in vascular expansion (H-Asp-Arg-Val-Tyr-Ile-His-Pro-OH).
ACE2 can also break down many other spheres, including de-spheric acid 9, apelin, neurodegenerate, A-sphericide, and stomach hunger.
ACE2 can also regulate the transmission of the membrane of the neutral amino acid transfer protein SLC6A19 and is associated with Hartnup disease.
As a translaminal protein, ACE2 is the main entrance point for certain coronavirus entering cells, including HCoV-NL63; SARS-CoV (a resulting SARS virus); and SARS-CoV-2 (a resulting COVID-19 virus).
More specifically, SARS-CoV and SARS-CoV2’s S1 patch proteins combine with the enzyme structure area of ACE2 on the cell surface, leading to an intramuscular effect, allowing viruses and enzymes to be transmitted together into the nucleus inside the cell.
This entrance process also requires the host silicone protein enzyme TMPRSS2 to trigger the activation of S protein, which is currently studying whether the process can be suppressed as a potential therapy.Some people guess that lowering ACE2 levels in cells may help fight infection.
However, several professional associations and regulators recommend continuing to use standard ACE inhibitors and ARB therapy.
A system assessment and ultrasound analysis published on July 11, 2012 found that “the use of ACE inhibitors significantly reduces the risk of pneumonia by 34% compared to the control group.”
In addition, "for patients with a higher risk of pneumonia, especially those with stroke and heart failure, treatment with ACE inhibitors also reduces the risk of pneumonia.
Using ACE inhibitors is also associated with a decrease in pneumonia-related mortality, but the result is less reliable than reducing the overall pneumonia risk.
Reorganization ACE2 (rhACE2) is considered to be a new method for treating acute lungs damage, which appears to improve the acute respiratory disorders syndrome caused by liposucre and the pulmonary blood flow dynamic indicators and blood oxygen saturation.
RhACE2 in the human body has a half-life of approximately 10 hours, the start time is 30 minutes and the action process (duration) is 24 hours.
Some studies show that for patients with unbearable levels of renin-angiotensin (RAS) inhibitors or high levels of circulatory vascular stress II,rhACE2 may be a promising drug.rhACE2 injections have been evaluated in clinical trials for the therapeutic effect of acute respiratory disorder.
The b'COVID-19 app is a mobile software designed to address the 2019-20 coronavirus epidemic, helping to track the close contact and identify individuals who may have been exposed to the infection ("contacters").
Some regions and jurisdictions have developed or presented many applications with the support of the official government.
Many frameworks for building close contact tracking applications have been created.
Privacy issues have also attracted many sides, especially some systems need to track the geographical location of the application users.
Low-invasive alternatives include using Bluetooth signals to record the distance between users and other phones.
On April 10, 2020, Google and Apple jointly announced that they will integrate this feature that supports Bluetooth apps directly into Android and iOS operating systems.
In China, the government has jointly developed an app that supports citizens to check whether they have been exposed to COVID-19 patients.
The program is currently being used in more than 200 cities in China, while Singapore has launched an app called TraceTogether.
The app was developed by the local IT community, released as an open source software and will be transferred to the government.North Macedonia launched a Bluetooth-based app "StopKorona!", to track exposure to potential infected people and help medical institutions make a quick response.
The application is developed by the Northern Macedonian Department of Communications Technology and the Ministry of Health.
By April 14, 2020, the app is waiting for approval for Google Play Store and Apple App Store.
On April 12, the government announced that the close contact tracking application has entered the advanced development phase and will be put into use in the coming weeks. Ireland and France also plan to launch similar application ("StopCovid").
Australia and New Zealand are considering to develop a similar application based on Singapore’s TraceTogether app and BlueTrace protocol.Russia plans to launch a geographical barrier app for COVID-19 patients living in Moscow to ensure that patients don’t leave the home.
Professor of Security Engineering at the University of Cambridge, Ross Anderson, listed some practical problems that app systems may exist, including false positive errors, and it may be ineffective if only a small portion of the population uses the app.
In order to prevent the spread of misleading or harmful coronavirus applications, Apple has set restrictions on the types of organizations that can publish coronavirus-related applications in the Apple App Store, which is limited to “official” or other reputational organizations.
Google and Amazon have applied similar restrictions.
Privacy Defenders expressed concerns about the use of coronavirus applications to be monitored on a large scale, especially after the epidemic threat was eliminated, whether the monitoring infrastructure built to respond to the coronavirus epidemic should be dismantled.
Amnesty International and more than 100 other organizations call on restrictions on this surveillance.
